# sdramhighstress on real DE2 silicon — 2026-05-08

## TL;DR

`riski5-core-sdramhighstress` (BRAM-resident firmware writing the
proven-clean lower 6 MB at 4 KB stride and the suspect upper 2 MB
at 1 KB stride with a unique `addr ^ 0xDEADBEEF` pattern, then
read-back, then re-read after ~100 ms delay) **passes both phases
on real silicon** — `PASS2` reached with no `F<region><addr><exp><act>`
failure record.

Conclusion for #64 follow-up: the SDRAM data path itself is **not**
corrupting in the high 2 MB region for a single-bus-master firmware
running from BRAM. The corruption observed during Linux boot at
high addresses must therefore come from one of:

1. Concurrent fetch+data access patterns the kernel uses — kernel
   text/data both live in SDRAM, so during boot the Avalon master
   port is multiplexed across instruction fetch and load/store.
   This BRAM firmware never fetches from SDRAM, so it can't
   reproduce that pattern.
2. JTAG-Avalon-Master upload corruption — the kernel + DTB are
   loaded into SDRAM via JTAG-Avalon before the core starts
   running. This firmware writes from the runtime data port. If
   the upload path corrupts high addresses but the runtime data
   port doesn't, that explains the boot symptoms exactly.
3. Refresh-vs-page-allocator interactions specific to the kernel's
   access cadence (less likely given this firmware does ~3500
   writes touching the same row patterns).

Most-likely-cause priority for the next probe: (2) JTAG-Avalon-Master
upload integrity check — re-verify written-vs-readback bytes from
the host side at upload completion, with extra coverage of the
> 6 MB region.

## Setup

- Bitstream: `riski5-core-sdramhighstress` at commit `416afa6`
  (firmware in `0258127`).
- Board: Altera DE2 Cyclone II EP2C35F672C6, USB-Blaster on
  `[3-4.1]`.
- Clock domain split: bus 40 MHz / core 40 MHz / sdram 100 MHz
  (default Multi-PLL Phase E config).
- Firmware overlay: `firmware/phase1/CoreMark.hs` is replaced
  with a re-export of `HelloSdramHighStress`'s
  `helloSdramHighStressFirmwareWords` so the unchanged
  `-DFIRMWARE_COREMARK` path bakes the high-stress probe into
  imem (BRAM at 0x0000_0000). FetchPolicy stays at the BRAM-only
  default — no SDRAM fetch involved in this test.

## Captured UART output

```
B,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,................................................................................................................................,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,................................................................................................................................PASS1r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r,r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.r.PASS2
```

Decoding:
- `B` — boot byte (BRAM exec + UART alive).
- 24 × `,` — phase-1 low-region writes (1536 strides ÷ 64 dot rate).
- 128 × `.` — phase-1 high-region writes (2048 strides ÷ 16 dot rate).
- 24 × `,` + 128 × `.` — phase-2 immediate read-back, no failure.
- `PASS1` — phase 2 clean.
- 25 × `r,` + 128 × `r.` — phase-3 re-read after delay, no failure.
  (One extra `r,` vs phase 2 due to the boundary-stride dot
  emission off-by-one — cosmetic, not a corruption.)
- `PASS2` — phase 3 clean.

Total UART chars: 1 + 152 + 152 + 5 + 153 × 2 + 5 ≈ 621.

## Follow-up: JTAG-Avalon-Master upload-path probe (same date)

Re-flashed `riski5-core-linux-master` and ran the existing
`sdram-write-pattern-test.tcl` against it. Test exercises full
32-bit non-zero-upper writes, half-word LO and HI writes (the
old #146 bug), post-`0xFFFFFFFF`-reset writes, and cross-row
writes — every test address sits in `0x80700000`–`0x80800000`,
i.e. the upper end of the suspect 2-MB region. Result:

```
summary: 29 passed, 0 failed of 29 total
```

This **rules out the JTAG-Avalon-Master upload path** as the
source of the high-address corruption observed during prior
Linux boots — both 32-bit and 16-bit hi/lo writes commit
correctly across rows up to 0x80800000.

